The gaol of Newcastle was also periodically delivered, sometimes by the sheriff and sometimes by judges specially com- missioned.⁴ We get a little information from the rolls here printed of the comitatae or county court, which was held at Newcastle3 we learn that the comitatus was present at the assiae court and recorded the customs of the county; it also gave consent to provisions for the preservation of salmon.⁵

We find also that the owners of several baronies within the county did suit at this court,⁶ and there are instances of appeals of all kinds in the same court, at which the appellant had to follow at the three county courts next after the deed complained of was committed, otherwise his appeal failed. A case illustrative of the county court will be found on p. 195.
